{"question": "How much time does one Game Turn represent in Advanced Squad Leader (ASL), and how is a Game Turn structured?", "expected_answer": "Each Game Turn in ASL represents about two minutes of real time. It consists of two Player Turns (one for each side), and each Player Turn is divided into eight phases (Rally, Prep Fire, Movement, Defensive Fire, Advancing Fire, Rout, Advance, Close Combat) according to the basic Sequence of Play (rule A3)."}
{"question": "What is the stacking limit for infantry units in a single hex in ASL?", "expected_answer": "Each side may stack up to three squads (or their equivalents) plus up to four single-man counters (leaders or other SMC) in one hex without penalty. Exceeding this limit results in overstacking penalties (A5.1)."}
{"question": "How many Movement Factors does a normal Good Order squad have?", "expected_answer": "A Good Order multi-man infantry unit (squad) has a base movement allowance of 4 Movement Factors (MF) in its Movement Phase. Inexperienced squads have a reduced allowance of 3 MF (rule A4.11)."}
{"question": "When are broken units forced to rout, and what happens if a broken unit cannot rout to a safe location?", "expected_answer": "A broken unit must rout during the Rout Phase if it is adjacent to a Known, unbroken enemy unit, or if it is in Open Ground and within the normal range and line of sight of a Known enemy unit (rule A10.5). If a broken unit cannot find a legal path to rout away under those conditions, it will be eliminated for Failure to Rout."}
{"question": "How is a Sniper activated in ASL, and what is the Sniper Activation Number (SAN)?", "expected_answer": "Each scenario defines a Sniper Activation Number (SAN) for each side (usually in the range of 2–7). When a player makes an original dice roll equal to the opponent's SAN during certain actions (like morale checks or attacks), it triggers a Sniper attack (rule A14.1)."}
{"question": "What is Point Blank Fire (PBF) in ASL and when does it apply to infantry attacks?", "expected_answer": "Point Blank Fire (PBF) is a firepower bonus for being at very close range. If an infantry unit is adjacent to its target, its attack firepower is doubled due to PBF (rule A7.21)."}
{"question": "During the Advancing Fire Phase, at what firepower do moving units attack compared to the Prep Fire Phase?", "expected_answer": "In the Advancing Fire Phase (AFPh), units that moved (and did not fire in Prep Fire) attack at half of their normal firepower (rule A3.5)."}
{"question": "What are the steps involved when firing ordnance (such as an anti-tank gun) at a target in ASL?", "expected_answer": "Ordnance fire involves a two-step process: First, a To Hit (TH) roll is made using the gun's To Hit number adjusted for range and target type (rule C3.1). If successful, a damage roll determines the effect, either against infantry on the Infantry Fire Table or against vehicles using the To Kill Table (rule C3.3)."}
{"question": "Can a vehicle enter a woods hex in ASL, and if so, what is required for it to do so?", "expected_answer": "Vehicles can enter woods hexes but must spend all their movement points and make a Bog check to determine if they get stuck (rule B13.41)."}
{"question": "How can a squad split into two half-squads (deploy) during a scenario?", "expected_answer": "A squad can deploy into two half-squads during the Rally Phase if a Good Order leader is present. The squad must pass a Normal Task Check (NTC) to successfully deploy (rule A1.31)."}
{"question": "How do Japanese squads differ from others when it comes to breaking under fire?", "expected_answer": "Japanese squads do not have a traditional broken side. Instead of breaking, they use \"step reduction.\" This means when a full-strength Japanese squad fails a Morale Check (and isn't eliminated outright), it flips to its reduced-strength side rather than breaking. A reduced-strength Japanese squad that fails a Morale Check is replaced by an unbroken half-squad. In effect, Japanese squads lose manpower (reduce in size/quality) instead of becoming broken units."}
{"question": "What happens to a full-strength Japanese squad if it fails a Morale Check?", "expected_answer": "If a full-strength Japanese squad (that is not berserk) fails a Morale Check (and does not suffer a casualty elimination), it undergoes step reduction. The squad counter is flipped to its reduced-strength side (marked with a red stripe) but remains in Good Order (unbroken). Essentially, the squad shrinks to a smaller but still-functioning unit instead of breaking and running."}
{"question": "What happens if a reduced-strength Japanese squad fails another Morale Check?", "expected_answer": "A reduced-strength Japanese squad that fails a Morale Check is step-reduced further – it is exchanged for an unbroken half-squad. In game terms, the original squad counter is removed and replaced by one of its half-squad counters (in Good Order). This represents the squad taking casualties and shrinking rather than collapsing. Only Japanese squads (and their infantry crews) use this rule – most other nationalities would simply break or be eliminated when failing morale."}
{"question": "Do Japanese conscript squads follow the same step-reduction rules as other Japanese squads?", "expected_answer": "Not exactly. Japanese conscript (Green) squads still attempt step reduction when failing Morale Checks, but they have an exception: if a conscript squad fails a Morale Check by more than its ELR (Experience Level Rating), it doesn't get to stay on the board as a reduced unit – it is effectively eliminated (representing it breaking completely). In practice, that means conscript Japanese squads are more brittle. They might break (or be removed) in situations where higher-quality Japanese squads would just step-reduce. Aside from that extreme case, conscripts still flip to a half-squad on a normal failed MC like other Japanese squads."}
{"question": "Can Japanese squads ever become broken units?", "expected_answer": "Under normal circumstances, Japanese full squads do not become broken – they reduce in steps instead. However, there are rare situations (for example, a Conscript squad failing beyond ELR, or a squad that suffers a casualty reduction and fails a morale check on top of that) where a Japanese unit could end up broken or eliminated. Also, Japanese half-squads (once a squad has been reduced) break and rally like normal units. But a full Japanese squad will usually never sit on the map with a \"broken\" side showing; it'll either be reduced to a half-squad or still be in good order. The design simulates the Japanese tendency to fight until effectively destroyed rather than surrender or fall back."}
{"question": "What does the horizontal red stripe on a Japanese squad counter signify?", "expected_answer": "The horizontal red stripe on a Japanese squad counter indicates it's on its reduced-strength side. Japanese squads have two steps: a full-strength step (front side) and a reduced-strength step (back side with the red stripe). If a full-strength squad fails a morale check (and doesn't die), you flip it to the red-striped side. That side typically has lower firepower and sometimes lower morale. The red stripe is a visual reminder that this squad has already taken casualties but is still fighting (unbroken). Non-Japanese squads do not have this two-step system (they just break), so the red stripe is unique to Japanese step-reduction."}
{"question": "How do Japanese half-squads behave in terms of breaking and rallying?", "expected_answer": "Once a Japanese unit has been reduced to a half-squad, it behaves mostly like a normal infantry unit. Japanese half-squads can break (they don't have a further 'reduced' side) and can rally using standard rules. One notable difference is that Japanese half-squads do not suffer Disruption – if they are unable to rout, they can become Disrupted rather than surrendering (a state unique to Japanese). Also, two Japanese half-squads of the same type in the same hex can recombine back into a full squad during the Rally Phase if in good order. But unlike full squads, these half-squads do not step-reduce further; a failed morale check will break them normally."}
{"question": "Can two Japanese half-squads recombine into a full squad?", "expected_answer": "Yes. In the Rally Phase, two Good Order Japanese half-squads of the same type (same quality and unit type) in the same hex can recombine to form a full-strength squad of that type. This is similar to the normal recombination rules for half-squads (A1.32). The result would be a full squad on its full side (not reduced). This ability allows Japanese to rebuild some losses if conditions permit. It's subject to the usual restrictions (both halves must be good order, same unit type, etc.). Recombination for Japanese basically reverses the step-reduction if you can get two reduced halves back together."}
{"question": "Do Japanese infantry crews also use step reduction like squads do?", "expected_answer": "Yes, Japanese infantry crews (the ones manning support weapons or guns) use a similar two-step concept. A Japanese crew counter has a full-strength side and a reduced-strength side (often a 2-2-8 full, 1-2-8 reduced). If a full-strength Japanese infantry crew fails a Morale Check, it flips to its reduced side instead of breaking. If a reduced-strength crew fails a Morale Check, it is step-reduced into a broken vehicle crew counter (essentially the crew abandons its position and is considered a normal broken crew). Also, a Japanese crew that breaks voluntarily (like failing a task check to abandon a gun) is often replaced by a broken vehicle crew immediately. The key is that Japanese crews try not to become \"broken infantry\" on the map – they either stay in play (possibly reduced) or are replaced by a generic broken crew that can't fight until rallied."}
{"question": "What happens to a Japanese infantry crew if it fails a Morale Check while already reduced?", "expected_answer": "A reduced-strength Japanese infantry crew that fails a Morale Check undergoes one more step reduction: it is replaced by a broken vehicle-crew counter (usually a 1-2-7 broken crew). In other words, the crew is no longer functioning as an infantry unit at that point – they've essentially been put out of action (broken) and are treated as a vehicle crew (which can eventually rally and maybe re-man a vehicle, but not operate as an infantry crew anymore). This broken crew has to rally like any other broken unit and is considered a vehicle crew for rules purposes. So a full-strength crew goes to reduced (still unbroken) on a failed MC, and a reduced crew goes to a broken crew (broken unit) on a failed MC."}
{"question": "Can Japanese vehicle crews continue fighting on foot if their vehicle is knocked out?", "expected_answer": "Yes. If a Japanese tank or vehicle is destroyed but the crew survives, the surviving crew appears on the map and, unlike many other nationalities, they are expected to continue fighting. In ASL, a Japanese vehicle crew that survives a bailout can operate as an infantry crew unit. Furthermore, if that tank had an Armor Leader, Japanese rules allow that leader to emerge as a normal leader on foot (with a slightly reduced leadership rating) and keep fighting with the infantry. This reflects Japanese doctrine that crews should join the battle as infantry when their vehicle is lost. Other nationalities' armor leaders typically are removed when their tank is KO'd, but Japanese armor leaders can become on-map leaders. Also, Japanese vehicle crews have normal infantry capabilities once out (though low firepower), and they do not break easily (they behave akin to other Japanese units, possibly even becoming heroic). So yes, Japanese crews fight on foot if able."}
{"question": "Why don't Japanese leaders break in the normal way when hit by enemy fire?", "expected_answer": "Japanese single-man counters (leaders and heroes) do not have a broken morale side at all. If a Japanese leader fails a morale check, instead of breaking and routing, he becomes wounded (flip to the wounded side, if he wasn't already wounded). Essentially, Japanese leaders will fight until they are physically unable – they won't \"run\" in game terms. This is to model the historical unwillingness of Japanese officers to retreat or surrender. So a Japanese leader will be killed or wounded in action rather than break and rout away. (If a Japanese leader is already wounded and suffers another break result, he is eliminated, as per normal rules for double wounds or casualty MCs). The upshot is: you'll never see a Japanese leader with a \"broken\" counter; he'll either stand (possibly wounded) or be gone."}
{"question": "What happens to a Japanese leader if he fails a Morale Check?", "expected_answer": "When a Japanese leader fails a Morale Check, he does not break. Instead, he suffers a wound. You flip the leader to his wounded side (reducing his leadership by one and movement by half, typically) and then make a wound severity roll to see if it's a light or serious wound. If he was already wounded and would be wounded again (or if he rolls poorly on the severity), that eliminates the leader (essentially, he dies of the wounds). The key is, a Japanese leader never becomes a \"broken\" unit that routs. He will either continue fighting (wounded or not) or be eliminated. This makes Japanese leaders very resilient in terms of morale – they'll stay in the fight until they physically can't."}
{"question": "Can Japanese leaders ever rout or voluntarily break?", "expected_answer": "No, Japanese leaders (and other single-man counters like heroes) cannot voluntarily break and do not rout after failing Morale Checks. If faced with a situation where most units would break and flee, a Japanese leader instead gets wounded (or eliminated if already wounded). Japanese units also often operate under a No Surrender attitude, so they won't voluntarily surrender either. In practical terms, if a Japanese leader is with broken troops, he might stay and die with them rather than rout away. The only time you'd see a Japanese SMC \"rout\" is if he was disrupted (a special case), but normally they either stand or they're gone. So, Japanese leaders do not run to the rear – they fight on or perish."}
{"question": "Are Japanese single-man counters (SMC) affected by Pin results or Pinned Task Checks?", "expected_answer": "Japanese SMC (like leaders) are generally immune to normal Pin effects from fire. They do not take Pinned Task Checks (PTCs) at all – if a PTC is called for, a Japanese SMC just ignores it (they won't pin from it). The only exceptions are very specific cases (like a wound or a hut collapse causing a pin). But typically, you will not see a Japanese leader get pinned by ordinary fire. They either remain active or end up wounded. However, note that if a Japanese SMC is concealed and gets a PTC, he could lose concealment (any unit would in that case), but he still wouldn't be \"pinned\". The rationale is that Japanese officers were extremely difficult to suppress. So in game terms, no, they basically don't pin from PTCs or normal pin results (except rare exceptions such as a hut collapse debris pin or voluntarily if doing certain actions like minimum move, etc.)."}
{"question": "How can a Japanese Armor Leader continue to participate after his tank is destroyed?", "expected_answer": "If a Japanese tank with an Armor Leader is knocked out and the crew survives, that Armor Leader can appear on foot as a normal leader in the hex where the tank was destroyed. Uniquely, Japanese Armor Leaders are not removed from play when their vehicle is lost. Instead, the owning player may place a leader counter (with one lower leadership modifier – e.g., a 9-1 AL becomes a 9-0 leader) with the surviving crew. This represents the tank officer dismounting and continuing to fight alongside infantry. This is a national characteristic of the Japanese; other nations' armor leaders typically do not get to continue leading on foot in ASL. The Japanese leader who \"unsaddles\" in this way functions like any other infantry leader from that point onward (albeit wounded in terms of reduced rating). It's a way to keep highly motivated leadership in play despite losing the tank."}
{"question": "What is a Japanese \"Tank-Hunter Hero\" and how is one created during play?", "expected_answer": "A Tank-Hunter Hero (often abbreviated T-H Hero) is a special kind of one-man hero unit that the Japanese can deliberately create to attack enemy armor. During play, if a Good Order Japanese squad or half-squad is sufficiently close to an enemy AFV (within 8 MF in the Movement Phase or adjacent in the Advance Phase, etc.), it can declare an attempt to create a T-H Hero. The Japanese player rolls a die: on a result of 3 or less (with some modifiers: -2 if the unit has a DC to give, +1 if it's just a half-squad, +2 if conscript), a Hero counter is immediately placed with that unit. That hero is designated as a Tank-Hunter Hero – essentially a soldier grabbing explosives or an anti-tank weapon for a suicide attack. A T-H Hero is marked and must target a specific enemy vehicle (the nearest one in LOS when created). He then can move (if during Movement) or immediately engage in Close Combat against that vehicle. T-H Heroes have special bonuses in CC vs vehicles (like a -1 DRM on the CC roll and the ability to use an AT Mine on a dr of ≤4). If the creation dr fails (especially if an original 6 is rolled), the attempt fails and the unit is typically pinned (unless it's already berserk from a Banzai). This rule reflects the historical Japanese practice of individuals volunteering to sacrifice themselves to destroy enemy tanks."}
{"question": "What prerequisites must be met for a Japanese unit to attempt to create a Tank-Hunter Hero?", "expected_answer": "To create a Tank-Hunter Hero, a Japanese infantry squad or half-squad must be in position to reach an enemy armored fighting vehicle. Specifically, it must either be within 8 Movement Factors of a known enemy AFV during the Japanese Movement Phase, adjacent to an enemy AFV at the start of the Advance Phase, able to conduct a CC Reaction Fire against an AFV during the enemy Movement Phase, or be the defending unit in Close Combat in the same hex as an enemy vehicle. The unit attempting this must be in Good Order (not broken or pinned) and not already marked with something like a Prep Fire or First Fire counter. Also, the unit can't be doing something else like carrying a heavy support weapon (overburdened) that turn. If those conditions are met, the player can roll to try to generate a T-H Hero. So in short: you need a ready Japanese infantry unit near a tank and an opportunity (phase) to launch the heroic attack."}
{"question": "What happens if the die roll to create a Japanese Tank-Hunter Hero is successful?", "expected_answer": "If the attempt is successful (Final die roll ≤ 3 after applicable modifiers), a hero counter is immediately placed in that unit's hex, and that hero is designated as a Tank-Hunter Hero. This hero is essentially a one-man unit with 10 morale that will attack an enemy AFV. The Japanese player must designate which enemy vehicle becomes the T-H Hero's target (usually the one that allowed the hero's creation, i.e., the nearest qualifying AFV). From that point, during the rest of that phase, the hero can act. For example, if created in the Movement Phase, the T-H Hero can continue moving (it doesn't expend MF to be created) toward that tank without drawing Defensive Fire for the creation moment. If created in the Advance Phase, the hero can immediately advance into the hex with the target if adjacent. In Close Combat, a T-H Hero has a strong chance to kill a tank (they attack on the vehicle's rear target facing with a -1 DRM and can use an AT Mine on a dr ≤ their ATMM number if they had one). Essentially, a successful creation means a new hero unit appears and will make a singular focused attack on the chosen enemy vehicle."}
{"question": "What special advantages or equipment might a Japanese Tank-Hunter Hero have?", "expected_answer": "In game terms, when a Japanese Tank-Hunter Hero is created, it is assumed he arms himself with whatever anti-tank weapon he can (which could be an explosive charge, an anti-tank mine (ATMM), a Molotov cocktail, etc.). The rules abstract this as follows: if the hero's creation roll was good enough (often if the original squad had a DC, the hero is given that to use with a -2 creation bonus), the hero effectively has an AT capability. For attacks, the T-H Hero is treated as having an effective weapon like an AT Magnetic Mine (ATMM) by default. On the Close Combat Table, he gets to use a -1 DRM in CC vs the vehicle (like a berserk bonus) and can employ the special ATMM attack: typically, if he rolls ≤ 4 on 1d6 (with some modifiers for target armor), the vehicle is immediately eliminated. The rule notes this 'ATMM' actually stands in for any of a variety of special anti-tank methods – it doesn't literally have to be a magnetic mine; it could represent a pole charge, lunge mine, bundle of grenades, etc. The point is, the hero has a one-shot high chance method to kill a tank. If the hero was spawned from a unit carrying a DC, then that hero might instead carry that DC into CC, which is also very deadly. Also note: a T-H Hero is considered berserk for movement, so he can't be pinned or stopped until he reaches the target."}
{"question": "What is a \"DC Hero\" in the context of Japanese special attacks, and how is it related to a Tank-Hunter Hero?", "expected_answer": "A \"DC Hero\" is essentially a Tank-Hunter Hero who is specifically armed with a Demolition Charge. If a Japanese squad possessing a DC successfully creates a hero (via the hero creation die roll, which gets a -2 modifier if the unit has a DC to hand over), that hero is assumed to take the Demolition Charge. This DC Hero will then try to rush the target (be it a tank or perhaps a bunker) and detonate the charge in Close Combat. In rules terms, a DC Hero is handled under the same Tank-Hunter Hero rule (G1.421) – the difference is just that his method of attack is a placed DC rather than an AT mine. The effects are dramatic: a DC hero who manages to detonate his charge in the target's hex will attack on the 30-column, usually more than enough to destroy most targets. It's effectively a one-man human bomb. The rule exists to reflect historical instances of Japanese soldiers carrying explosive charges to sacrifice themselves blowing up tanks or strongpoints. In ASL, both DC Heroes and ATMM Heroes are created with the same mechanism; it's just what they carry that differs."}
{"question": "How does a Japanese Banzai Charge work in ASL?", "expected_answer": "A Banzai Charge is the Japanese version of a Human Wave attack. It allows Japanese infantry to move in a mass assault to close the distance to the enemy. When a Banzai Charge is declared at the start of the Japanese Movement Phase, all participating units (which can be as few as one or as many as a chain of squads) must move toward a designated enemy unit or hex as fast as possible. They get bonus movement capabilities: they ignore terrain penalties (each unit gets a number of MF equal to the slowest unit's normal allotment for each hex they will move into). They also become Fanatic while charging (they won't break or pin while moving). Essentially, the Banzai units move together in a wave, and the enemy can fire at them with Defensive First Fire as normal (potentially at many targets). At the end of the movement, if they survive, the Japanese units can end up adjacent to or even in the same hex as enemy units to initiate Close Combat in the Advance Phase. So in summary: a Banzai Charge is a special movement tactic to rush the enemy en masse, trading potential casualties for a chance to close distance rapidly."}
{"question": "Can a single Japanese soldier carry out a Banzai Charge alone?", "expected_answer": "Yes. Unlike a normal Human Wave (which requires at least 3 squads in line), a Banzai Charge in ASL can be declared by even a single Good Order Japanese unit. If only one unit Banzais, it essentially acts like a berserk charge for that unit (with the Banzai movement benefits). Of course, Banzai Charges can include multiple units too – often many squads chain together. If multiple squads from different hexes join, they must form a contiguous chain of adjacent units. Importantly, if more than one multi-man unit is involved in a Banzai, at least one leader must be part of the charge to lead them. But for the minimum case, yes – one Japanese squad or even one Japanese leader on his own can yell \"Banzai!\" and charge forward using the Banzai rules."}
{"question": "What conditions must be met to declare a Banzai Charge in ASL?", "expected_answer": "To declare a Banzai Charge, it must be the Japanese player's turn (Movement Phase) and they must have at least one Good Order Japanese infantry unit eligible. They choose a target enemy unit or hex that the Banzai will be directed at (within LOS or at least known position). All Japanese units that are going to participate must be currently unpinned, unbroken, and not berserk (berserk units already have their own behavior). If multiple units participate, they need to form a continuous chain of adjacency so the wave is linked (one unit must be adjacent to another in the wave). Additionally, if the wave has any squads (MMC) and more than one unit, a leader must be included (if it's just one squad alone, no leader is needed; but if it's, say, three squads, you need a leader charging with them). Once those conditions are set, the Japanese player announces the Banzai Charge and designates the units that will Banzai and the target. Then movement for those units proceeds under the Banzai rules."}
{"question": "What effects do Japanese units suffer after performing a Banzai Charge?", "expected_answer": "After a Banzai Charge movement, all Japanese units that participated are marked with a \"Lax\" marker for the remainder of that player turn. Being Lax means they temporarily lose their Stealth advantage (so they're easier to ambush in close combat and slightly easier to detect). This represents the disorder and fatigue following the charge. During the charge itself, the units were Fanatic (essentially berserk-like, they wouldn't pin or cower and had enhanced CC abilities). But once their movement is over (they've reached the enemy or as far as they could go), they are winded. In practical terms, this Lax status can make them more vulnerable to enemy actions later in the turn (like in close combat, the enemy gets a bonus to ambush them because they're Lax). The Lax marker is removed at the end of that player turn. So basically: they charge in fearless, but afterwards they're a bit disorganized (Lax) until the turn ends."}
{"question": "How is an Ambush determined in Close Combat in ASL?", "expected_answer": "At the start of Close Combat (CC) in a hex where opposing units are present, each side rolls one six-sided die for ambush determination. You compare the final results (after applying any ambush modifiers). If one side's roll is 3 or more less than the other's, that side has achieved an ambush. If the difference is less than 3 either way, no ambush occurs. The side that ambushes gets significant benefits: they can attack first in CC (and the enemy can't attack back in that CC phase), or they can even withdraw from the hex before CC if they prefer. If neither side ambushes, CC is simultaneous as usual. Essentially, ambush is a function of beating the opponent's ambush die roll by a margin of 3."}
{"question": "What modifiers can influence the Ambush die roll?", "expected_answer": "Several factors modify ambush rolls. If a unit is Stealthy (e.g., elite troops, Japanese infantry, Partisans), it gets a -1 modifier to its ambush die roll, making it more likely to ambush. If a unit is concealed at the moment of CC, it gets a -2 modifier (a big advantage). Conversely, certain conditions give penalties: for example, if the hex is jungle, bamboo, or kunai (dense terrain), the *attacker* in CC gets a +1 penalty (because the defender is harder to catch by surprise there). Also, units that are Lax (e.g., Banzai units that just charged) suffer a +1 on their ambush roll. These modifiers are cumulative. So, a concealed, Stealthy defender in dense terrain could have -3 or more to its roll, whereas an attacking unit in that situation might have +1. That heavily tilts the chance of ambush toward the defender. You apply all applicable modifiers, then compare the final die results to see if one side succeeds by 3 or more."}
{"question": "Why might radio communications be unreliable in Pacific jungle warfare?", "expected_answer": "The hot, humid environment of the Pacific had detrimental effects on radio equipment. Moisture and fungus could corrode circuits and batteries, and the dense jungle foliage could physically block or dampen radio waves. In some ASL scenarios, this is reflected by making radio contact attempts harder or increasing the chance of radio breakdown. Historically, units in thick jungle often had trouble maintaining radio contact. For example, scenario special rules might require a radio contact roll to succeed on a lower number in jungle terrain or impose a penalty if it's raining and humid. So in summary: tropical climate and heavy vegetation often made radios less reliable, and ASL often accounts for that by slight modifications to contact or maintenance rolls for radios in PTO scenarios."}
{"question": "What are Trip Flares and when can they be used in ASL scenarios?", "expected_answer": "Trip flares are small devices that the defending side (notably U.S. forces in late-war night scenarios) can place in likely enemy approach paths. In ASL, trip flares are used in PTO night scenarios (typically 1944-45) by a defending player who has them available in the order of battle. Before play, the defender secretly records hexes (usually jungle, bamboo, or wire hexes) where trip flares are set. During play, if an enemy unit enters or moves within one of those hexes, the defender makes a die roll to see if a flare is triggered. If it is (roll is ≤ number of flares in hex), a Trip Flare counter is placed in that hex, and it illuminates that hex (and surrounding hexes depending on depression/elevation) for the rest of the Player Turn. This sudden illumination negates the darkness in that area, exposing units to fire as if it were daylight in that hex. The trip flare typically burns for the Player Turn and is removed in the next turn's advance to CC Phase. In short, trip flares allow a night scenario defender to automatically light up infiltrating enemy units at critical moments, offsetting the attacker's concealment advantage at night."}
{"question": "How did the Japanese Anti-Tank Magnetic Mine (ATMM) differ from the German ATMM in effectiveness?", "expected_answer": "The German AT Magnetic Mine (like the Hafthohlladung) used a shaped-charge warhead that could penetrate significant armor when attached to a vehicle, making it quite lethal to tanks. The Japanese \"AT Mine\" was often a smaller explosive (sometimes not a true shaped charge) – more akin to a heavy explosive charge or lunge mine. It had less penetrating power and was generally only effective against lightly armored vehicles or the tracks/undercarriage of tanks. In ASL, when a Japanese Tank-Hunter Hero uses an 'ATMM' attack, it's not literally always a magnetic mine – it represents any close-range improvised anti-tank method (lunge mine, pole charge, etc.). These Japanese methods were less reliable than German magnetic mines. Game-wise, the German ATMM has a higher chance to kill a tank (represented by needing a lower dr), whereas the Japanese one might have a smaller chance or require the target to be relatively thin-skinned. Historically, Japanese close-assault weapons needed a brave soldier to get right on the tank to inflict damage, and often they would disable a tank (mobility kill) rather than brew it up. So, in summary: the German ATMM was a sophisticated shaped charge very deadly to armor, the Japanese AT approaches were cruder and less guaranteed, which is reflected in ASL by differences in success probabilities for those attacks."}
{"question": "Will Japanese troops surrender in ASL, or do they fight to the last man?", "expected_answer": "Japanese units rarely surrender in ASL. By rule, Japanese infantry will become Disrupted (a special state) instead of surrendering if they cannot rout and would normally be forced to surrender. Also, opponents often invoke No Quarter when fighting the Japanese (meaning they won't accept a surrender anyway). So in practice, Japanese units fight until eliminated. They do not voluntarily surrender, and if surrounded with no escape, they usually get eliminated (or marked with a Disrupted counter, which means they are out of play but not captured). It's very uncommon to see Japanese units as POWs in an ASL scenario. Only in very unusual circumstances (like a completely surrounded, broken Japanese unit with an enemy not invoking No Quarter) could a surrender occur, and even then the Japanese player has options like self-disruption to avoid it. Essentially, the game models that Japanese fought to the last and seldom surrendered."}
{"question": "What does the \"No Quarter\" rule mean and how does it commonly apply to Japanese forces?", "expected_answer": "\"No Quarter\" (NQ) means a side has declared it will not take prisoners. In game terms, when a player invokes No Quarter, enemy units that would normally surrender (for example, broken units that cannot rout) are instead eliminated (\"killed\"). Once No Quarter is in effect, the opposing side is also freed from the obligation to surrender – their units will attempt to Disrupt or Low Crawl away instead of giving up. In Pacific scenarios, it's almost assumed that No Quarter is in effect: Japanese historically did not expect or give quarter. Often the scenario rules or just player choice at first opportunity leads to No Quarter being active (e.g., Japanese might massacre any prisoners or the US player might declare NQ upon first chance of capture). The practical result: you usually won't have prisoners on the Pacific battlefield. Japanese broken units will try to withdraw or become Disrupted rather than surrendering, and Allied troops likewise might fight to the death if they know surrender means massacre. So, \"No Quarter\" ensures a fight to the finish on both sides."}
{"question": "Are Australian and New Zealand (ANZAC) troops represented differently in ASL?", "expected_answer": "ANZAC troops are typically represented with British/Commonwealth counters and follow British rules, but there is one noteworthy distinction: Australian and New Zealand infantry are considered Stealthy (as per A11.17) in many scenarios. For example, in PTO scenarios, ANZAC units often get a stealth rating, making them a bit more effective at ambush and remaining concealed. Otherwise, their weaponry and organization use British equipment (Lee-Enfield rifles, Bren guns, etc.), so there's no special counter mix for ANZAC. But scenario special rules often note \"ANZAC squads are Stealthy\". Historically, these troops were well-trained and often used patrol tactics, which is reflected by that Stealthy status. So in game terms: treat ANZAC as British for most things, but remember they have that stealth advantage (and possibly a different leadership generation number reflecting national characteristics). Other than that, they fight as normal Commonwealth forces."}
{"question": "What is an \"Observation Tank\" (OP tank) and what is it used for in ASL?", "expected_answer": "An Observation Tank (denoted by \"OP\" in its name) is a vehicle modified to act as a spotter for artillery rather than as a direct combat vehicle. In ASL, some scenarios or orders of battle include OP tanks – typically they have minimal armament (maybe just machine guns or a dummy gun) and a higher likelihood to have radios. They serve as mobile observers for off-board artillery (OBA). For example, the Germans had Panzer III OP and Panzer IV OP variants used to spot for artillery batteries. In game terms, an OP tank can serve as a forward observer: it can drive to a good vantage point and call in fire missions using its onboard radio, often without drawing as much attention since its offensive threat to enemy armor is low. It cannot really fight other tanks effectively (the OP variants usually have no functional main gun), so you wouldn't use it in a tank duel. Instead, you protect it and use it to coordinate artillery strikes. These vehicles cease to exist as combat units once the crew bails out (their only purpose was to carry the radio). So, an OP tank in ASL is only for improving your OBA capability on the move."}
{"question": "How do towed guns represent their limbered (moving) state in ASL?", "expected_answer": "Many artillery pieces in ASL are depicted with two sides on their counter: the front shows the gun in firing position, and the back shows it \"limbered\" (towed/trailers folded). When a gun is limbered, it's essentially hooked up to a prime mover (truck, halftrack, horses, etc.) and is being transported. In game terms, a limbered gun cannot fire. It moves using the movement of the towing vehicle or by manhandling if no vehicle. To limber or unlimber a gun, you typically spend a certain number of movement points (depending on the gun size). Once limbered (flip to the limbered side), you then move the gun as a unit with its tow. When it reaches where you want it, you spend time to unlimber (flip it back to firing side). Some guns (usually heavy AA or AT guns) have a limbered side printed – for example, the 105mm howitzer has its reverse side as a limbered silhouette. If a gun's back side is blank or just shows a breakdown number, it means that gun doesn't have a limbered mode (usually smaller support weapons that are always manhandled). In summary: flipping to the limbered side indicates the gun is being moved and can't shoot until unlimbered again."}
{"question": "How does beach terrain affect movement and combat in ASL?", "expected_answer": "Beach terrain is typically open ground with some special attributes. For infantry, a beach hex provides no cover (no TEM), so moving on a beach can be very dangerous under fire (it's like moving in Open Ground – you could be subject to FFMO and Interdiction). For vehicles, beaches, especially those defined as \"soft sand,\" often force Bog Checks. In many scenarios, when a vehicle enters a beach hex that is soft sand, it must roll for bog (it might get stuck in the sand). Vehicles also pay extra movement points in sand. For example, some scenario might say soft sand costs double MP or has a bog modifier. In terms of combat, beach hexes don't hinder LOS (they're open) but might be at a lower elevation (if coming out of water). Sometimes surf conditions or tide can be scenario factors on beaches too. But generally: infantry on a beach are very exposed, vehicles on a beach risk bogging, and there's no concealment on a beach unless night or smoke. It basically recreates why rushing across a beach under fire is so deadly."}
{"question": "How do Red Chinese (Communist) units differ from Nationalist Chinese units in ASL?", "expected_answer": "In ASL, Nationalist Chinese forces (Kuomintang) use the Chinese Army counters (like 3-3-7, 4-4-7 squads, etc.) and follow standard rules for an organized army. Communist Chinese (Red Chinese) are often represented using Partisan counters or treated like Partisans in terms of special rules. For instance, Red Chinese squads might be considered Stealthy and subject to the Partisan \"automatic concealment gain\" benefits, reflecting their guerilla tactics. Red Chinese also have restrictions: they cannot utilize Off-board Artillery (OBA) at all (whereas Nationalists can, albeit limited). Also, their leadership might be slightly different. In point-based scenarios, Red Chinese squads have a BPV one higher than equivalent Partisan squads (since they're marginally better equipped than generic partisans). Nationalist Chinese, on the other hand, can have heavier weapons, trucks, some armor (esp. if aided by Allies) and can use OBA (with some scarcity). So if you see a scenario with \"Red Chinese,\" expect them to behave a lot like Partisans (think higher stealth, no artillery, emphasis on close combat), whereas \"Nationalist Chinese\" behave more like a conventional force (though often green). In summary: Reds = more guerilla-like, Nationalists = more standard but often lower quality troops."}
{"question": "In a DYO scenario, why must players agree on the historical month and year before purchasing forces?", "expected_answer": "Because the date determines what equipment is available or appropriate. In ASL, many weapons and vehicles have introduction dates and availability that change over time. By setting a specific historical date, players know which units can be purchased (for example, no buying a 1944 tank in a 1942 scenario). The date can also influence rarity of equipment and Experience Level Ratings. For instance, a scenario set in early 1942 means late-war advanced weapons are off-limits. Additionally, the year might modify the Basic Point Values (BPV) or Rarity Factors of certain items (some get cheaper or more common later in the war). So, agreeing on the month/year ensures both players purchase historically plausible forces and use the correct costs for that time frame. It basically sets the \"tech level\" and availability for the DYO."}
{"question": "What is a 'Rarity Factor' (RF) in the context of purchasing units?", "expected_answer": "Rarity Factor (RF) is a mechanism used in some ASL campaign games or DYO systems to adjust the cost or availability of units based on how common or rare they were historically. An item with RF 1.0 is baseline; RF above 1 means it's rarer (thus either more expensive or requires a roll to get), RF below 1 means it's common (cheaper or easier to get). For example, a certain tank might have RF 1.2 in 1943 (meaning it was rare then, so you pay 20% more or have a harder availability roll), but by late 1944 its RF drops to 0.8 (it's more abundant, so cheaper/easier to obtain). In some DYO rules, you multiply the unit's BPV by the RF to get its adjusted purchase cost. In others, you use RF as a die-roll target to see if you can get that unit at all. Not every scenario uses RF (most published scenarios have fixed OBs so no need). It's mainly in flexible purchase systems or historical campaigns. RF is essentially a balancing tool to reflect historical scarcity."}
{"question": "If you attempt to purchase a rare piece of equipment in DYO and it's not available, what happens to the points you spent?", "expected_answer": "In a DYO, if you spend points on something that requires an availability roll (due to rarity) and that roll fails, those points are lost. You don't get a refund or a chance to immediately buy something else with them. This represents the idea that you tried to allocate resources to get that rare item, but it didn't come through. For example, you attempt to buy a big artillery module that needs an availability dr and you fail the dr – that artillery doesn't show up and the points you set aside for it are lost."}
{"question": "What is the difference between Close Combat (CC) and Melee in ASL?", "expected_answer": "Close Combat is resolved in the Close Combat Phase, and if neither side is eliminated, the units remain in Melee, preventing them from moving or firing until one side is eliminated or retreats."}
{"question": "What happens when a unit enters an enemy-occupied hex?", "expected_answer": "The units engage in Close Combat, resolved during the Close Combat Phase. If neither side is eliminated, they remain locked in Melee."}
{"question": "How does stacking affect Close Combat?", "expected_answer": "Stacking limits apply in Close Combat. Overstacked units suffer penalties to attack rolls and are more vulnerable to enemy attacks."}
{"question": "What is a Berserk unit, and how does it behave?", "expected_answer": "A Berserk unit must move toward and engage the nearest enemy unit in Close Combat. It gains bonuses for movement and attacks but cannot take cover."}
{"question": "How does an Entrenched unit defend differently in ASL?", "expected_answer": "An Entrenched unit receives extra protection by gaining a terrain advantage. It is harder to hit with Direct Fire and enjoys improved morale checks."}
{"question": "What is Wall Advantage and how does it work?", "expected_answer": "Wall Advantage allows a unit behind a wall or hedge to gain a defensive bonus while still being able to fire at enemy units on the other side."}
{"question": "How do night rules affect visibility in ASL?", "expected_answer": "At night, Night Visibility Range (NVR) limits how far units can see. Illuminated hexes and Starshells can extend visibility but also reveal units."}
{"question": "What is a Starshell, and how does it impact gameplay?", "expected_answer": "A Starshell is a flare that temporarily illuminates a group of hexes, increasing visibility in the dark and potentially exposing hidden units."}
{"question": "How do prisoners function in ASL?", "expected_answer": "Prisoners are captured Broken units that cannot act on their own. They must be guarded by Good Order units, and if left alone, they may attempt to escape."}
{"question": "Can prisoners be rescued in ASL?", "expected_answer": "Yes, prisoners can be rescued if friendly units eliminate or capture their guards, allowing them to rejoin their side as Broken units."}
{"question": "What is a Hero, and how does it differ from a regular unit?", "expected_answer": "A Hero is a single-man unit with enhanced morale and firepower. Unlike leaders, they do not provide leadership bonuses but are harder to break."}
{"question": "What happens when a vehicle is Abandoned?", "expected_answer": "An Abandoned vehicle remains in place but can no longer be operated until a crew re-enters it. It may be captured by enemy forces."}
{"question": "How do Gun Crews differ from standard infantry units?", "expected_answer": "Gun Crews are specialized MMCs that operate ordnance and receive benefits such as improved To Hit rolls and self-rally capabilities."}
{"question": "What is the difference between an Immobilized and a Bogged vehicle?", "expected_answer": "A Bogged vehicle may attempt to recover and move again, while an Immobilized vehicle is permanently stuck and cannot move for the rest of the game."}
{"question": "How does the Buttoned Up (BU) status affect a vehicle crew?", "expected_answer": "A BU crew has better protection but reduced visibility and firepower. They cannot use certain weapons and have penalties to spotting and combat."}
{"question": "How does a Light Mortar differ from a regular squad's firepower?", "expected_answer": "Light Mortars fire indirectly, can place smoke, and require a To Hit roll, unlike standard squad fire."}
{"question": "What is a Gyrostabilizer and how does it affect a vehicle's fire?", "expected_answer": "A Gyrostabilizer allows a vehicle to fire more accurately while moving, reducing the movement penalty on To Hit rolls."}
{"question": "How do Rowhouses impact movement between buildings?", "expected_answer": "Rowhouses provide connected building hexes, allowing movement between them without exposing units to open ground."}
{"question": "What is a Rarity Factor (RF) in ASL?", "expected_answer": "The Rarity Factor (RF) is a value that adjusts the cost or availability of units based on their historical rarity. Units with higher RF values are more expensive or harder to obtain in DYO scenarios."}
{"question": "How does a Cactus Patch hex affect movement?", "expected_answer": "A Cactus Patch hex costs 2 MF for infantry to enter and is treated as Dense Jungle for most purposes, including providing +1 TEM and hindering LOS."}
{"question": "What are the effects of Alpine Hills on movement?", "expected_answer": "Alpine Hills are steep and difficult to traverse, requiring additional MF to climb and potentially causing Exhaustion checks for infantry units."}
{"question": "What is a Design Your Own (DYO) scenario in ASL?", "expected_answer": "A DYO scenario allows players to create custom battles by purchasing forces with points, following historical date restrictions and rarity factors."}
{"question": "How do historical date requirements affect DYO scenarios?", "expected_answer": "Historical date requirements restrict which units and equipment can be purchased based on their availability during specific time periods of WWII."}
{"question": "What is the difference between a Scenario Defender and Scenario Attacker?", "expected_answer": "The Scenario Defender typically sets up first and often receives defensive benefits like prepared positions, while the Scenario Attacker moves first and usually has offensive victory conditions."}
